`IHtmlHelper` has a [`ViewContext`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.aspnetcore.mvc.rendering.ihtmlhelper.viewcontext?view=aspnetcore-2.2#Microsoft_AspNetCore_Mvc_Rendering_IHtmlHelper_ViewContext) property, which itself has a [`HttpContext`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.aspnetcore.mvc.actioncontext.httpcontext?view=aspnetcore-2.2#Microsoft_AspNetCore_Mvc_ActionContext_HttpContext) property. With this, you can use [`GetRequiredService`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.extensions.dependencyinjection.serviceproviderserviceextensions.getrequiredservice?view=aspnetcore-3.0) to get hold of `IHostingEnvironment`. Here&#39;s an example:

    htmlHelper.ViewContext.HttpContext.RequestServices.GetRequiredService&lt;IHostingEnvironment&gt;();

This isn&#39;t DI: it&#39;s using the Service Locator pattern, which is often called an [antipattern](https://blog.ploeh.dk/2010/02/03/ServiceLocatorisanAnti-Pattern/). If you want to use DI, consider creating a [Tag Helper](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/mvc/views/tag-helpers/authoring?view=aspnetcore-3.0) instead of an `IHtmlHelper` extension method. That would also mitigate the need to nest all of those property access calls.

